---
layout: base
title: "Our Services"
description: "We provide culturally grounded legal services for Indigenous peoples. We partner with Indigenous nations
and organizations globally to advance sovereignty, human rights, and social justice through advocacy, research, and
capacity-building."
date: 2023-11-21
serviceCards:
  - title: "Archival Work"
    link: "/contact/"
    description:
      The American Indian Law Alliance (AILA) documents and preserves Indigenous peoples’
      participation in international forums such as the United Nations Permanent Forum on Indigenous
      Issues (UNPFII) by digitizing records, testimonies, and media through digital platforms
      safeguarded for future generations, while honoring community protocols for stewardship and
      guardianship.
  - title: "Cultural Renewal & Mutual Aid"
    link: "/programs/cultural-renewal/"
    description:
      AILA supports cultural renewal and mutual aid by strengthening community ties and ensuring
      cultural traditions are passed on to future generations. This includes elders’ luncheons,
      intergenerational learning spaces, family food boxes, coat and gift giveaways, and
      back‑to‑school programs—embodying a gift economy rooted in reciprocity and balance.
  - title: "Missing and Murdered Indigenous Relatives"
    link: "/programs/mmiw/"
    description:
      The crisis of Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women, Girls, and Two‑Spirit relatives
      (MMIW/MMIR) is rooted in colonization and worsened by systemic failures. Many cases are
      misclassified, never entered into national databases, or lost between jurisdictions, leaving
      families with slow or no response and limited media attention.
  - title: "Language Classes"
    link: "/contact/"
    description:
      Through Haudenosaunee language classes, AILA fosters the preservation and revitalization of
      Indigenous languages as central to identity and governance.
---

